description:
secretx-keyring/src/lib.rs:259-273 (`from_uri_field_selector_rejected`) uses an explicit `match` block:

```rust
let result = KeyringBackend::from_uri("secretx:keyring:my-app/api-key?field=token");
match result {
    Err(SecretError::InvalidUri(msg)) => {
        assert!(msg.contains("keyring does not support ?field="), ...);
    }
    Err(e) => panic!("expected InvalidUri, got: {e}"),
    Ok(_) => panic!("expected InvalidUri, got Ok"),
}
```

Every other URI-validation test in the same file uses `assert!(matches!(...))`. Example from line 232-238:
```rust
assert!(matches!(
    KeyringBackend::from_uri("secretx:keyring:onlyone"),
    Err(SecretError::InvalidUri(_))
));
```

The `match` here is justified by the substring assertion on the message — `matches!` cannot bind `msg`. So the pattern is necessary; what is not necessary is the verbosity. Idiomatic Rust would write:

```rust
let Err(SecretError::InvalidUri(msg)) = KeyringBackend::from_uri(...) else {
    panic!("expected InvalidUri");
};
assert!(msg.contains("keyring does not support ?field="));
```

`let-else` is stable since 1.65, well within the workspace MSRV of 1.75. Reads more clearly: declares the binding once, asserts the substring once.

Net: -8 lines, easier to read.
